text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: No, Valley Girls are not stupid%0a:Author: roochis%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 19:25%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-022006-363860#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:20-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-022006-363860#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDefending "Valley Girl Speak"%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://youtu.be/EMnfnD5xcoM %0a^This is a short video making fun of the “Valley Girl Accent”%0a%0aThe description box summarizes it as “Two Valley Girls meet on the street and exhaust their entire vocabulary in under 45 seconds.”%0a%0aThis video heavily implies that women who use a "Valley Girl Accent" are shallow and  unintelligent. %0a%0a“Valley Girl Speak” or “Valley Girl Accent” refers to speech patterns similar to the California Dialect (Valley refers to the San Fernando Valley). This term originally portrayed women who use it as upper-class, shallow, and materialistic. However, today, the phrase “Valley Girl” or “Valley Girl Speak” comes with the implication that the woman who uses it is an airhead. %0a%0a	Some characteristics of “Valley Girl Speak” include: %0a%0a- High Rising Terminal (aka up talk) This is when statements have rising intonation, and often, declarative statements sound like questions. %0a%0a- Creaky phonation (aka vocal fry) %0a%0a-Using “like” as a discourse marker (filler word) %0a%0a%0aThe most distinct feature of “Valley Girl Speak” is High Rising Terminal. Surprisingly, this is a phenomenon that has been studied in England, Australia, and New Zealand. Some linguistics believe it originated in the 1950s and others believe it’s centuries old (aka older than the 1980s Valley Girl caricature). Even though “Valley Girl Speak” is almost exclusively used to describe women, men use rising intonation as well. While making simple declarative statements, men and women were found to use rising-intonation similarly. %0a%0aSources: %0a%0ahttps://www.wm.edu/as/sociology/news-events/news-archive/2013-14-archive/overturning.the.myth.of.valley.girl.speack.php%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valley_girl%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
